elon_tweets_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(elon_tweets_df['date'])
elon_tweets_df.set_index('date').resample('M').size().plot(kind='line', figsize=(10, 6))
plt.title('Elon Musk Tweet Activity Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Tweets')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

#Top 10 Most Liked Tweets
most_liked_tweets = elon_tweets_df.nlargest(10, 'likes_count')
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(most_liked_tweets['tweet'], most_liked_tweets['likes_count'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Likes Count')
plt.title('Top 10 Most Liked Tweets by Elon Musk')
plt.show()


# Combine likes, replies, and retweets to calculate total engagement
elon_tweets_df['total_engagement'] = elon_tweets_df['likes_count'] + elon_tweets_df['replies_count'] + elon_tweets_df['retweets_count']

# Group by date and sum up the total engagement
engagement_over_time = elon_tweets_df.groupby('date')['total_engagement'].sum()

# Plot total engagement over time
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
engagement_over_time.plot(color='blue')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Engagement')
plt.title('Total Twitter Engagement Over Time')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Overall Trend: The stock value starts at a lower point in 2014 and remains relatively stable until around late 2019. Starting around early 2020, there is a sharp increase in stock value. The value peaks around 2021 before displaying volatility with several peaks and troughs.

Covid-19 Impact: The red dashed vertical line represents the start of the Covid-19 pandemic (around 2020). Despite initial fluctuations, Teslas stock value surged during the pandemic.

Post-Pandemic Recovery: After reaching a peak in late 2021, the stock value showed fluctuations. It remained above pre-pandemic levels, indicating sustained recovery.

def train_prophet_model(data):
    model = Prophet(
        changepoint_prior_scale=0.05,
        holidays_prior_scale=15,
        seasonality_prior_scale=10,
        weekly_seasonality=True,
        yearly_seasonality=True,
        daily_seasonality=False
    )
    model.add_country_holidays(country_name='US')
    model.fit(data)
    return model

def generate_forecast(model, periods=365):
    future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=periods)

    return forecast

Section 3 Question: How do Elon Musk's tweets affect stock market Movements? Can this sentiment be measure though sentiment analysis?

In[207]:
import re
from textblob import TextBlob

# Function to remove emojis from text
def remove_emojis(text):
    emoji_pattern = re.compile("["
                               u"\U0001F600-\U0001F64F"  # emoticons
                               u"\U0001F300-\U0001F5FF"  # symbols & pictographs
                               u"\U0001F680-\U0001F6FF"  # transport & map symbols
                               u"\U0001F1E0-\U0001F1FF"  # flags (iOS)
                               u"\U00002500-\U00002BEF"  # chinese char
                               u"\U00002702-\U000027B0"
                               u"\U00002702-\U000027B0"
                               u"\U000024C2-\U0001F251"
                               u"\U0001f926-\U0001f937"
                               u"\U00010000-\U0010ffff"
                               u"\u2640-\u2642"
                               u"\u2600-\u2B55"
                               u"\u200d"
                               u"\u23cf"
                               u"\u23e9"
                               u"\u231a"
                               u"\ufe0f"  # dingbats
                               u"\u3030"
                               "]+", flags=re.UNICODE)
    return emoji_pattern.sub(r'', text)

# Modify clean_text function to remove emojis
def clean_text(text):
    text = re.sub(r'\n', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\xa0', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\t', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'https\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'pic.twitter\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'#\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'@\S+', '', text)
    text = remove_emojis(text)  # Remove emojis
    text = text.strip()
    text = ' '.join(text.split())
    text = text.lower()
    return text

# Apply sentiment analysis to the cleaned tweet text
elon_tweets_df['cleaned_tweet'] = elon_tweets_df['tweet'].apply(clean_text)

from collections import Counter
import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

# Download stopwords if not already downloaded
nltk.download('stopwords')

# Get the set of stopwords
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

# Tokenize positive tweets
positive_words = ' '.join(positive_tweets['tweet']).lower().split()
# Tokenize negative tweets
negative_words = ' '.join(negative_tweets['tweet']).lower().split()

# Remove stopwords
positive_words = [word for word in positive_words if word not in stop_words]
negative_words = [word for word in negative_words if word not in stop_words]

# Count occurrences of each word
positive_word_counts = Counter(positive_words)
negative_word_counts = Counter(negative_words)

# Get top 10 words for positive and negative tweets
top_10_positive_words = positive_word_counts.most_common(10)
top_10_negative_words = negative_word_counts.most_common(10)

print("Top 10 words from positive tweets:")
for word, count in top_10_positive_words:
    print(f"{word}: {count}")

print("\nTop 10 words from negative tweets:")
for word, count in top_10_negative_words:
    print(f"{word}: {count}")

import pandas as pd

# Filter data for the years 2018 to May 2021
tesla_stock_filtered = tesla_stock_df[(tesla_stock_df['date'].dt.year >= 2018) & (tesla_stock_df['date'] < '2021-06-01')]
dogecoin_filtered = dogecoin_df[(dogecoin_df['date'].dt.year >= 2018) & (dogecoin_df['date'] < '2021-06-01')]

# Group by week and calculate weekly average closing prices
tesla_weekly_avg = tesla_stock_filtered.resample('W-Mon', on='date')['close'].mean()
dogecoin_weekly_avg = dogecoin_filtered.resample('W-Mon', on='date')['close'].mean()

# Calculate weekly change in price for Tesla and Dogecoin
tesla_weekly_change = tesla_weekly_avg.diff()
dogecoin_weekly_change = dogecoin_weekly_avg.diff()

# Ensure all arrays have the same length
length = min(len(tesla_weekly_avg), len(dogecoin_weekly_avg), len(tesla_weekly_change), len(dogecoin_weekly_change))

# Create a new DataFrame with weekly averages and changes
weekly_summary_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Date': tesla_weekly_avg.index[:length],
    'Tesla_Weekly_Avg_Close': tesla_weekly_avg.values[:length],
    'Dogecoin_Weekly_Avg_Close': dogecoin_weekly_avg.values[:length],
    'Tesla_Weekly_Price_Change': tesla_weekly_change.values[:length],
    'Dogecoin_Weekly_Price_Change': dogecoin_weekly_change.values[:length]
})

# Print the new DataFrame
print(weekly_summary_df.head())

tesla_slope, tesla_intercept, _, _, _ = linregress(weekly_summary_df.index, weekly_summary_df['Tesla_Weekly_Avg_Close_Normalized'])
dogecoin_slope, dogecoin_intercept, _, _, _ = linregress(weekly_summary_df.index, weekly_summary_df['Dogecoin_Weekly_Avg_Close_Normalized'])

plt.plot(weekly_summary_df['Date'], dogecoin_slope * weekly_summary_df.index + dogecoin_intercept, '--', color='b', label='Dogecoin Regression Line')
plt.plot(weekly_summary_df['Date'], sentiment_slope * weekly_summary_df.index + sentiment_intercept, '--', color='g', label='Sentiment Regression Line')
